@{JLEFT}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Window" "AmigaDOS For Beginners - Using AmigaDOS For Beginners - Window Size & Line Lengths"

@{B}@{U}@{JCENTER}AMIGADOS FOR BEGINNERS

USING AMIGADOS FOR BEGINNERS - WINDOW SIZE & LINE LENGTHS@{UB}@{UU}
@{JLEFT}

I have @{"already mentioned" LINK "Windows"15} that your Multiview/Amigaguide window should be
sized to show about 24 lines of text.

As not all people use the same versions of Amigaguide or Multiview, I
cannot rely on the Amigaguide command WORDWRAP to properly word wrap
paragraphs. (WORDWRAP only works with amigaguide.library v39 and later).

I have therefore formatted the articles so that each line that appears
in the window has a maximum of 75 characters with a line feed at the end
of each line rather than only at the end of each paragraph. This should
allow each line to be displayed in a window that has the same width as your
screen provided that you are not using a font size bigger than 8.

Of course, if a @{"cross reference" LINK "Cross"} takes you to read an @{"example script" LINK "ADB:Parts_41-50/Example-47.1/Main"} file
that is an actual AmigaDOS script rather than a copy of it within an article
then you could very well have text going beyond the right edge of the
window. If I put line feeds into the scripts to make them fit in the
window then it would corrupt the script and it would not work!

But if lines are extending beyond the right edge of the window when reading
the articles you may have to do one or more of:-

- widen the window to the full width of the screen

- reset your screen preferences to a width of 255 pixels at least

- reset the "Fonts" preferences to set the "system Default Text" font
  to a size of 8 or less.

If you are using the standard preferences that came with your Amiga then
you should not have any problems.


@{JCENTER}=== End of Text ===
@{JLEFT}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Examples" "AmigaDOS For Beginners - Using AmigaDOS For Beginners - Example Scripts"

@{B}@{U}@{JCENTER}AMIGADOS FOR BEGINNERS

USING AMIGADOS FOR BEGINNERS - EXAMPLE SCRIPTS@{UB}@{UU}
@{JLEFT}
At times I have example scripts in an article. These scripts are also
saved to disk as separate files. This is to save you typing in the script
yourself. The script files have the same number as the article number,
followed by a number indicating whether it is example number 1 or number 2,
etc., for that article. For example, the article:-

   30.QUIT

has these three example scripts:-

   Example-30.1
   Example-30.2
   Example-30.3

The example script files are in the same directories as the articles
to which they belong.

Except for Examples 33-1, 33-2 and 33-3, none of the example script files
have icons. These three only have icons because they are there to illustrate
how to operated scripts from an icon (See @{"ICONX" LINK "ADB:Parts_31-40/33.IconX/MAIN"} article).

@{B}Changing The Current Directory@{UB}

To use the example scripts, go to your @{"Shell/CLI" LINK "ADB:Misc/Glossary/CLI_&_Shell"} window and use the
@{"AmigaDOS" LINK "ADB:Misc/Glossary/AmigaDOS"13} command @{"CD" LINK "ADB:Parts_01-10/07.CD/Main"} to change the current directory to that in which the
examples are held. To do so, use one of these command lines:-

  > CD ADB:Parts_01-10
  > CD ADB:Parts_11-20               @{B}Note@{UB}   ADB: is a  @{"logical device" LINK "ADB:Misc/Glossary/LogicalDevices"}
  > CD ADB:Parts_21-30                      that is assigned when you
  > CD ADB:Parts_31-40                      @{"first double click" LINK "Assignment"} on the
  > CD ADB:Parts_41-50                      INDEX icon.
  > CD ADB:Parts_51-60
  > CD ADB:Parts_61-70
  > CD ADB:Parts_71-80


@{B}Executing The Scripts@{UB}

Provided that you have already used the CD command to change the current
directory, all you need do to execute the desired example script is to
enter in the Shell/CLI window:-

  > ScriptName

For example, to execute Example-27.1 you would enter:-

  > Example-27.1

If you get one of these messages (which, in all likelihood, you will @{B}not@{UB}
get @{B}unless@{UB} you are using AmigaDOS @{B}v1.2 or earlier@{UB}):-


 With @{B}v1.x@{UB} - Unable to load Example-xx.x: file is not an object module.
 With @{B}v2+@{UB}  - Example-xx.x: file is not executable

then try entering:-

  > Execute Scriptname

Then have a read of the section of @{"Part 25 - Setting The `S' Bit" LINK "ADB:Parts_21-30/25.Script_Files/Setting"}.

Don't worry too much about it now. By the time that you have read through
to the first script example in the article @{"SCRIPT_FILES" LINK "ADB:Parts_21-30/25.Script_Files/MAIN"} you should have
a far better idea of how to enter the above example command lines.

AmigaDOS @{B}v1.2 and earlier@{UB} users @{B}must always@{UB} use the EXECUTE command even
when the text of the articles say just to enter the script name.


@{JCENTER}=== End of Text ===
